@node TECH "Program Information"

TRasH 80 is written in a mixture of C and 68020 Assembler

SAS 6.57 and PHXass (freeware) were used respectively in development, with
CED V3.5 the editor of choice.

Gadget Handling, program loading/snapshot , keyboard emulation are in C.
The Z-80 emulator and the Screen write routines are written in assembler and
run as a seperate process on their own.

The Z-80 core uses an "instruction pipelining" system, not dissimilar to that
used in the excellent "APPLE2000" by Kevin Kralian. While tending to be rather
memory hungry, speed wise it is very efficient.

ASL.library is used for the file requesters as nothing elaborate was required
on the 1 Bitplane TRaSh 80 screen.

The Z-80 HALT instruction will currently terminate program operation.



@endnode

